Citation.sTitle: Salt Effect on Ethanol-Based Aqueous Biphasic Systems Applied to Alkaloids Partition: An Experimental and Theoretical Approach
Citation.sAbstract: Aqueous biphasic systems (ABS) based on alcohol-salt are of signi cant interest be- cause of their low cost and environmental impact, as well as their higher selectivity and fast phase segregation, when compared to a polymer-salt ABS. The salt e ect was eval- uated in ethanol-based aqueous biphasic systems using ve di erent salts (NaH2PO4, K2HPO4, K3PO4, K2CO3 or K3C6H5O7) at 298.15 K and atmospheric pressure. The results suggest that both cation and anion nature present in uence on liquid-liquid equilibrium (LLE). In order to describe experimental LLE data, NRTL model was used to adjust the experimental data, which has shown a good t (rmsdless than0.68%). Salt in- uence in ABS and its partition ability was accounted by phase diagrams, as well as a partition study using nicotine and ca eine. Results have shown high partition yield and high selectivity.
